
What is Cloud Computing?

Cloud Computing is the delivery of computing resources such as servers, storage, databases, networking, security, and software over the internet on a pay-as-you-go basis.

Traditionally, companies purchased physical servers and maintained them in their own data centers. Cloud computing eliminates this requirement by allowing organizations to rent infrastructure from cloud providers like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.

Why Cloud Computing?
Traditional Infrastructure Problems
High initial investment
Hardware maintenance costs
Limited scalability
Data center management
Power and cooling expenses
Disaster recovery complexity
Cloud Benefits
Pay only for usage
Global accessibility
High availability
Elastic scalability
Improved security
Faster deployment
Real-Time Scenario

A startup launches an e-commerce website.

Traditional Method:
Buy Server
Install OS
Configure Network
Purchase Storage
Maintain Hardware

Time Required: 2-4 Weeks

Cloud Method:
Create AWS Account
Launch EC2
Deploy Application
Go Live

Time Required: 15 Minutes

